2,document:local-pdf,,,race forward ¬ª,file://research_results/documents/raw/c441d095b5efadcac83eadd5ad604240.pdf,research_results/documents/parsed/c441d095b5efadcac83eadd5ad604240.txt,c441d095b5efadcac83eadd5ad604240,57355,third_party:batch_parallel,2025-12-31T03:31:06.925466,ocrmypdf_force+pdftotext,equity(21); people of color(19); racial justice(10); diversity(6); minority(6); inclusion(3),policy(7); must(4); standard(3); contract(2); rule(1); statewide(1),,"in addition, shifting demographics make even more urgent our need to speak openly about racial bias and inequity, and their deep roots in our history, culture, and institu- tions. | THE GUIDE INCLUDES: Covering Key Issues With a Racial Lens Seven Harmful Racial Discourse Practices Key Terms & 31 Concepts Online Resources 35 Appendix W Covering Key Issues With a Racial Lens It is critical that media coverage on race bring an explicit racia | ¬´ Beware of using terms like ‚Äúmajority-minority‚Äù as they do not give a nuanced or accurate picture of the demograph- ic changes occurring ina particular community. | e Avoid terms that may subtly, yet profoundly, evoke and reinforce racial stereotypes, such as ‚Äúurban,‚Äù ‚Äúlazy,‚Äù ‚Äúhard- working,‚Äù ‚Äúentitlement,‚Äù and others, ¬´ Consider barriers to mobility, including practices that appear race neutral in intent, but have racial","‚Ä¶children of color being subject te more extreme disciplinary measures. ¬¢ Speak in depth with all players, beyond politicians, policy makers, and paid experts. ¬´ ‚ÄòTalk to parents and students, teachers, advocates on the ground who have been working on t‚Ä¶ | ‚Ä¶titu- tions. This system of racialization‚Äîwhich routinely confers advantage and disadvantage based on skin color and other characteristics ~must be clearly understood, However, when race enters our public conversations about these important national issues, the dialogue is too often‚Ä¶","‚Ä¶ctory, experiences, and outcomes. in addition, shifting demographics make even more urgent our need to speak openly about racial bias and inequity, and their deep roots in our history, culture, and institu- tions. This system of racialization‚Äîwhich routinely confers advantage and disad‚Ä¶ | ‚Ä¶ens up new avenues of inquiry and storytelling. This section highlights pressing, and often under- reported, issues that disparately impact people of color, and provides tips and guidelines to help avoid pitfalls often found in media coverage. Be explicit about race. Avoid stereotypes. Use a‚Ä¶"
