assigned a co‚Ä¶"
2,third-party:content,www.osba.org,application/rss+xml; charset=UTF-8,"<?xml version=""1.0"" encoding=""UTF-8""?><rss version=""2.0"" xmlns:content=""http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/"" xmlns:wfw=""http://wellformedweb.org/CommentAPI/"" xmlns:dc=""http://",https://www.osba.org/feed/,research_results/documents/parsed/592c84071aa2e1e2c199fe14a36d610c.txt,592c84071aa2e1e2c199fe14a36d610c,51615,third_party:www.osba.org,,,equity(12); diversity(1); underserved(1),rule(24); policy(6); statewide(5); must(3); required(3); requirement(3),community engagement(2),"If the district hasn‚Äôt met targets by the fifth year, ODE will be able to control up to 25% of a district‚Äôs funding.</p> <p>ODE taking control of a quarter of district‚Äôs spending raises complicated budget questions considering that more than 80% of most distri | More than three dozen Thursday and Friday sessions included immediately relevant topics such as policies for artificial intelligence in education, serving students in the wake of equity-related federal actions, Oregon legislative updates, special education and | &nbsp;</p> <p>This year, the conference offered six ‚Äúessential learning strands‚Äù so school leaders could concentrate their understanding in areas including student rights, policy and legislation, and governance and leadership.</p> <p>OSBA attorneys from multip | ‚ÄúKnowing the requirements and the limits the law places on schools helps school boards make better decisions and policy,‚Äù</p> <p>&#8211; Jake Arnold, OSBA<br><a href=""mailto:jarnold@osba.org"">jarnold@osba.org</a></p> <p>The post <a href=""https://www.osba.org/e","‚Ä¶for school accountability with Senate Bill 141. The State Board of Education will likely vote Thursday, Dec. 11, on the first major set of rules...</p> <p>The post <a href=""https://www.osba.org/state-board-of-education-takes-measure-of-what-accountability-means/"">State Board of Educ‚Ä¶ | ‚Ä¶ference offered six ‚Äúessential learning strands‚Äù so school leaders could concentrate their understanding in areas including student rights, policy and legislation, and governance and leadership.</p> <p>OSBA attorneys from multiple departments were presenters in different strands. OSBA,‚Ä¶","‚Ä¶ay sessions included immediately relevant topics such as policies for artificial intelligence in education, serving students in the wake of equity-related federal actions, Oregon legislative updates, special education and immigration enforcement relating to schools.</p> <p>Krista Paren‚Ä¶ | ‚Ä¶elp students stay in school and graduate. He created a regional board training and mentorship program and has promoted greater school board diversity. He is deeply involved with the Oregon Association of Education Service Districts and hosts a monthly radio show with Mulvihill.</p> <p>In‚Ä¶"
